\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In chapter 4, seasonal composites depicted an “El Niño-like” pattern associated
 with extreme bushfire seasons in Victoria.
 This pattern was consistent from spring to summer.
 This chapter describes how the weather in spring influence bushfire danger
 and activity in summer.
 Linear correlations established the relationship between several bushfire
 variables from these two seasons.
 The investigation required four groups of data for these correlations:
 bushfire activity records, bushfire danger metrics, climate variables,
 and climate indices.
 Additionally, this chapter proposes a bushfire predictive tool: “Victorian
 Seasonal Bushfire Index” (VSBI).
 The VSBI is a simple index to forecast seasonal bushfire danger.
 The index uses bushfire weather variables and an ENSO index.
 The VSBI presents a moderate skill to forecast seasonal bushfire weather
 and activity.
 However, relative humidity on its own showed a storng predictive skill.
\end_layout

