\begin_layout Subsubsection
Formulation of the Victorian Seasonal Bushfire Index
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The VSBI represents a simplified relationship between bushfire weather variables
 and an ENSO index.
 This relationship links large-scale with local climate processes that produce
 bushfire conditions.
 The VSBI assumes a linear relationship between three bushfire weather variables.
 These variables are temperature, relative humidity and precipitation.
 The effect these variables on preconditioning bushfire occurrences was
 the main criteria for their selection (citation).
 The index also incorporates SST in the El NINO1+2 region as another variable.
 The index accounts for the effect of ENSO on bushfire conditions.
 The computation of the VSBI is the aggregation of sub-indices based on
 these variables.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The composites presented in chapter 4 revealed the seasonal patterns of
 each VSBI variable.
 Temperature, relative humidity and precipitation presented intense anomalies
 over Victoria (33S-36S; 145E-150E).
 Additionally, the NINO1+2 region (0-10S, 90W-80W) presented strong and
 also statistical significant anomalies.
 These anomalies link regional and global climate patterns to bushfire occurrenc
es in Victoria.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first step in computing the VSBI is calculating spatial averages over
 the gridded anomalies from these regions.
 Subsequently, these daily means were averaged for the seasons SON and DJF
 respectively.
 The period of analysis was period 1900-2010 for the 20CR and 1911-2011
 for HADISST data.
 On the other hand, the daily values of the six weather stations were averaged
 to calculate regional anomalies.
 This procedure allowed to calculate the VSBI sub-indices using weather
 station data.
 The available period of WS data was 1974-2010.
 The time series generated were divided by their standard deviation to normalize
 them.
 Finally, the VSBI was formulated in the following in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:VSBI"

\end_inset

.
 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:VSBI-calculation-procedure"

\end_inset

 shows the VSBI calculation procedure.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
