\begin_layout Subsubsection
Linear correlations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This chapter aims to establish the relationship between bushfire predictands
 and predictors.
 The investigation used a linear correlation analysis to establish these
 relationships.
 There were four groups of data compiled or generated in this investigation.
 These groups are bushfire activity records, seasonal bushfire danger metrics,
 climate variables and indices.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The correlation analysis used data from spring (SON) and summer (DJF).
 The exception was for bushfire activity records.
 The bushfire definition used accounts for extreme events.
 These events are not common in other seasons than DJF.
 Therefore, the number of events in spring was too low to include them in
 the analysis.
 For example, the DELWP database regitered 31 events during the DJF season
 over the period 1961-2011.
 The other three seasons of the year registered only 11 events during the
 same period.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The period of analysis was 1974-2010.
 The analysis used weather station and reanalysis data.
 The SAM index—AAO— was excluded from the analysis.
 The AAO did not show a significant correlation with most variables in a
 firts analysis undertaken for the period 1980-2010 (see appendix).
 Additionally, the VSBI was sensitive to the biases in precipitation in
 the 20CR data.
 Therefore, precipitation from weather stations substituted the 20CR data
 for the period 1974-2010.
 The figures show the statistically significant results at the 5% level.
\end_layout

