\begin_layout Subsubsection
Original seasonal FFDI computation (1974-2010)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The FFDI computed with WS data depict more extreme bushfire weather for
 Victoria than the calculation using the 20CR.
 This difference is likely to occur for several reasons.
 FFDI variables from renalysis data do not correspond exactly to surface
 values.
 Near- surface reanalysis data is available at the 1000 h-Pa level.
 Calculations using this data do not exactly represent surface level conditions.
 Additionally, the FFDI computed with weather station data use values at
 3 pm.
 Yet, reanalysis data for FFDI variables is available at 6-hourly intervals.
 These intervals limited the availability of data to 4 pm values.
 Moreover, there are intrinsic limitations in the reanalysis dataset already
 discussed in Chapter 2.
 The linear scaling techniques adjusted the biases without significantly
 altering the correlations.
 However, bushfire danger might vary if we use a different bushfire index.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An alternative index might show a different seasonal bushfire danger trend.
 Yet, the difference is unlikely to be significant.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Dowdy2009"

\end_inset

 determined that the FFDI could be comparable to the Canadian Fire Weather
 Index (FWI).
 The study compared the two indices for Australian conditions.
 The FWI is an internationally recognized fire weather index 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "VanWagner1987,VanWagner2005,Dowdy2009a"

\end_inset

.
 Therefore, the FFDI can be representative of bushfire weather conditions
 in Victoria.
 Nevertheless, the use of only one realization of the 20CR leaves non-quantified
 uncertainties.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 20CR reanalysis has 56 model realizations 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Compo2011"

\end_inset

.
 Every realization represents an equally possible state of the atmosphere
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Compo2011"

\end_inset

.
 Therefore, bushfire weather computed with a mean value realization has
 a degree of uncertainty.
 This uncertainty could be quantified.
 Thus, the bias-correction results are only valid for one possible state
 of the atmosphere.
 However, the seasonal bushfure weather computations show an increasing
 trend consistent with an atmosphere under a global warming process 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Stocker2013"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The increasing trend in seasonal bushfire danger computations for Victoria
 agrees with the results of other investigations for southeastern Australia
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Lucas2007,Hennessy2005,Hasson2009"

\end_inset

.
 In fact, climate change is extending the bushfire season in this region
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Clarke2011"

\end_inset

.
 However, the available data bases showed that most bushfires occur during
 DJF.
 Therefore, in this investigation the fire season was defined as the season
 December-January-February.
 Therefore, the results can change—although not significantly- if the bushfire
 season is extended (e.g.
 November-December-January-February-March—).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Bias-correction of bushfire weather variables (1974-2010)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Every bushfire weather variable showed a significant correlation between
 weather station and 20CR data.
 Temperature, relative humidity and wind speed presented a similar variability
 with differences in magnitude.
 The application of linear scaling techniques corrected the mean of these
 three variables.
 The results were satisfactory since the correlations did not significantly
 change—and in some cases even improved—.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Additionally, the bias-correction of reanalysis data produced similar outcomes
 in magnitude.
 Although, the bias-correction process yielded satisfactory results, weather
 station data was not homogenized.
 This is a limitation that is particularly evident for wind speed.
 The seasonal values fo this variable show an abrupt increase after the
 year 2000.
 The change in the technology to measure the variable might cause the inhomogene
ities (citation).
 On the other hand, linear scaling techniques did not correct biases in
 precipitation.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 20CR data does no accurately represents precipitation in Victoria.
 The linear scaling bias-correction techniques did not yield better results
 for this variable.
 Therefore, the FFDI computation did not use bias-corrected data for precipitati
on.
 However, the FFDI is less sensitive to changes to this variable 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Dowdy2009a"

\end_inset

.
 The lessened sensitivity might occur because the FFDI equation does not
 explicitly includes precipitation.
 This variable is part of the drought factor.
 This factor does not include precipitation explicitly either.
 The drought factor computation requires the calculation of moisture deficits.
 In this research, the use of the KBDI yields these deficits.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Bias-corrected seasonal FFDI computation (1974-2010)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
After the bias-correction, the magnitude of FFDI results is acceptable.
 However, after the bias-correction, the FFDI with reanalysis data slightly
 over-estimates seasonal bushfire danger.
 For most years, this over-estimation is not significant.
 Additionally, FFDIcum seems to be a better metric of seasonal bushfire
 danger than FFDI>25.
 The results with FFDIcum show a higher correlation between bushfire danger
 and activity.
 The result is consistent using reanalysis and weather station data.
 This result is also similar using bias-corrected data.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Extended seasonal FFDI computation (1920-2010)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The extended FFDI computation covered the period 1920-2010.
 The bias-correction used the adjustment factors determined for the period
 1974-2010.
 The calculation required finding the date with the higher precipitation
 to set the soil moisture deficit to zero.
 This factor is part of the KBDI calculation.
 After the computation, the correlation analysis covered only for the period
 1974-2010.
 For this period FFDI computed with station data was available.
 The results were moderately correlated and similar to those obtained before
 extending the results.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Additionally, the investigation selected the extreme bushfire danger seasons
 from 1920 to 2010.
 The selection of this extreme seasons used an 85th percentile criteria.
 The results showed that most extreme seasons occurred after 1951.
 This trend is consistent with the work of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Lucas2007"

\end_inset

 for southeastern Australia.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
However, there is greater uncertainty in the accuracy of the results.
 Certain variables could present even larger biases before the period 1974-2010.
 The difference might be significant for variables like wind speed because
 of the incorporation of new technologies to measure this variable.
 Additionally, after the bias-correction the seasonal FFDI underestimates
 bushfire danger.
 This FFDI result is not consistent with the overestimation yielded for
 the period 1974-2010.
 There is no weather station data to compare the fields for the period 1920-1973.
 Therefore, an alternative approach could be the validation against an independe
nt reanalysis product like ERA-clim 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Stickler2014"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Drivers of bushfire weather 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The relationship between variables in spring shows a significant influence
 of the IOD.
 These results agree with the findings of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Cai2009"

\end_inset

.
 Positive IOD events drive hot and dry weather conditions during spring
 in Victoria.
 These environmental conditions dry fuel loads.
 Dried fuel loads makes the summer season more prone to bushfires.
 The IOD exerts a stronger influence than ENSO in this season.
 This result also agrees with the findings of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Cai2009"

\end_inset

.
 However, there is a strong correlation between DMI with ENSO indices.
 Therefore, the IOD might not be independent of ENSO as other studies suggest
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Dommenget2002"

\end_inset

.
 In fact, ENSO indices show how El Niño events drive Victorian climate in
 spring.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Among the ENSO indices, El NINO 3.4 showed the strongest relationships with
 climate variables.
 This strong correlation reflects how the oceanic component of ENSO might
 drive bushfire weather.
 In fact, SST1.2 showed the strongest correlation with bushfire danger represente
d as FFDI>25.
 In the previous chapter, seasonal anomalies in this region showed statistically
 significant anomalies.
 These anomalies have a link with bushfire occurrences in Victoria.
 These patterns justified the decision to include the SST of this region
 in the VSBI formulation.
 In contrast, SAM does not have a significant influence on preconditioning
 bushfire seasons.
 The appendix shows the correlations for these variable.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The strong influence of SAM over rainfall in Victoria is well known 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Risbey2009a,Ho2011"

\end_inset

.
 Therefore, is an unexpected result the lack of influence of SAM over bushfire
 weather.
 The use of different climatologies could explain the weak influence of
 SAM (see Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:Sources-of-monthly-climate-indices"

\end_inset

).
 The climatology used for bushfire variables was 1961-2011.
 On the other hand, the climatology for SAM was 1979-2000.
 Although the correlation results for climate indices vary from spring to
 summer.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Overall, the correlations between climate indices and bushfire metrics in
 DJF are not strong.
 Thus, these results differ contrast with the results in the previous season.
 The influence of ENSO and IOD is greater in spring than summer.
 These modes of variability have more influence building-up fuels loads
 in spring, rather than exacerbating bushfire danger in summer.
 However, ENSO and IOD do not show much skill to forecast bushfire weather.
 The results are better for ENSO indices and DMI when correlated to fire
 activity.
 The different climatologies used for the calculation of the indices might
 influence this outcome.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Bushfire predictors 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Relative humidity and temperature in spring are strong predictors of bushfire
 metrics in summer.
 They have higher prediction skill than VSBI, FFDIcum and FFDI>25.
 Moreover, relative humidity is the variable that most influences bushfire
 danger in Victoria.
 This result is consistent using weather station and reanalysis data.
 Additionally, the correlations for relative humidity show similar results
 in the tests preformed—corelations in SON, DJF and from SON to DJF—.
 The analysis computed correlations in spring (SON), summer (DJF), and from
 spring to summer.
 This result agrees with the findings of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Harris2013"

\end_inset

using vapor pressure as predictor.
 However, it is worth acknowledging again that weather stations data was
 not homogenized.
 Additionally, precipitation from reanalysis data was not bias-corrected.
 Finally, it is also important to contrast this result with the skill of
 the VSBI as an integrated index.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The VSBI has a stronger prediction hability to predict bushfire activity
 than FFDI metrics.
 The forecasting skill of the index is higher using weather station data.
 However, the prediction skill is even higher for relative humidity on its
 own.
 The reduced computation complexity of the VSBI oversimplifies the relationship
 between bushfire weather variables.
 Indeed, the index's linear relationship assumption do not enhance its predictio
n skill.
 Eventhough, the amount of data used short—37 years—it is unlikely that
 the VSBI will show greater predictive skill using more years.
 Additionally, the choice of a short or extended bushfire season —DJF or
 NDJFM respectively—is also unlikely to change this result.
\end_layout

